election_record.label: New Hampshire 1824 Governor

overview.note: "Hon. DAVID L. MORRIL, if our calculation in the returns to be heard from be correct, and if the votes shall be fairly returned, is elected. He is the candidate who was most prominently nominated by the republicans, so far as partial nominations in several counties and districts could make him so, and is himself a decided democratic republican; but, on account of a misapprehension of his preculiar sentiments in regard to religious toleration, and because there was no general nomination, the votes of some of the best democratic towns in the State, votes which were never before lost to the republicans, have been thrown away in this election." New-Hampshire Patriot and State Gazette (Concord, NH). March 22, 1824.

sub_unit.name: Keene
sub_unit.note: Ezra Bartlett received 1 vote as E. Bartlett.

sub_unit.name: Rumney
sub_unit.note: Levi Woodbury received 33 votes as L. Woodbury.

sub_unit.name: Amherst
sub_unit.note: History of the Town of Amherst lists Jeremiah Smith with 27 votes.

sub_unit.name: Raymond
sub_unit.note: "Here Morril had one hundred and twenty-seven votes and Woodbury one, which was cast by Moses Dudley, Esq." The History of Raymond, N.H.. 50.
